  "prompt": "How is the part of the throat behind the nose called? What function does it serve?",
  "response": "The part of the throat behind the nose is called the **nasopharynx**. It is the uppermost section of the pharynx (throat) and is located above the soft palate, connecting the nasal cavity to the oropharynx.\n\n### Functions of the Nasopharynx:\n1. **Air Passage**: The nasopharynx serves as a passageway for air from the nasal cavity to the oropharynx and then to the larynx and trachea, facilitating breathing.\n\n2. **Drainage**: It provides drainage for the Eustachian tubes (which connect the middle ear to the nasopharynx) that help equalize pressure in the ears.\n\n3. **Protection**: The nasopharynx is lined with mucous membranes and cilia, which help trap and expel pathogens and debris, thus playing a role in protecting the respiratory system.\n\n4. **Immune Function**: The nasopharynx contains lymphoid tissue, including the adenoids, which are part of the immune system and help defend against infections.\n\nOverall, the nasopharynx plays a crucial role in both respiratory function and immune response.",
